06913nam a22010575i 9780823294374DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232943747 a10.1515/97808232943742doi  a(DE-B1597)577482  a(OCoLC)1263021931  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aBT265.3b.A855 2021 7aREL0170002bisacsh04a232/.322300aAtonement and Comparative Theology :bThe Cross in Dialogue with Other Religions /ced. by Catherine Cornille. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aComparative Theology: Thinking Across Traditions ;v900tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tWhy Atonement -- tWho Needs It? -- tChristian Atonement Enlightened by a Buddhist Perspective on Craving -- tHow Q 5:75 Can Help Christians Conceptualize Atonement -- tNot for Myself Alone: Atonement and Penance After Daoism -- tSuffering and the Scandal of the Cross -- tGod’s Suffering in the Hindu- Christian Gaze -- tMore Than Meets the Eye: The Cross as Maṇḍala -- tDivine Suffering and Covenantal Belonging: Considering the Atonement with Heschel and Moltmann -- tThe Clash and Continuity of Interpretation of Redemptive Suffering Between African Religions and Christianity -- tRethinking Redemption -- tRedemptive Suffering After the Shoah: -- tJudgment on the Cross: Resurrection as Divine Vindication -- t“At One or Not At One?” -- tHow Empty Is the Cross? -- tBibliography -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe central Christian belief in salvation through the suffering, death, and resurrection of Jesus Christ remains one of the most intractable mysteries of Christian faith. Throughout history, it has given rise to various theories of atonement, many of which have been subject to critique as they no longer speak to contemporary notions of evil and sin or to current conceptions of justice. One of the important challenges for contemporary Christian theology thus involves exploring new ways of understanding the salvific meaning of the cross.In Atonement and Comparative Theology, Christian theologians with expertise in Judaism, Islam, Hinduism, Buddhism, Daoism, and African Religions reflect on how engagement with these traditions sheds new light on the Christian understanding of atonement by pointing to analogous structures of sin and salvation, drawing attention to the scandal of the cross as seen by the religious other, and re-interpreting aspects of the Christian understanding of atonement. Together, they illustrate the possibilities for comparative theology to deepen and enrich Christian theological reflection.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAtonement. 0aChristianity and other religions. 4aReligion. 4aTheology. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh1 aBidlack, Bede Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBidlack, Bede Benjamin.1 aClooney, Francis X.1 aClooney, Francis X., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornille, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCornille, Catherine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCourau, Thierry-Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCourau, Thierry-Marie.1 aHeim, S. Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeim, S. Mark.1 aJoslyn-Siemiatkoski, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoslyn-Siemiatkoski, Daniel.1 aLefebure, Leo D.1 aLefebure, Leo D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul